    "More intuitively, the second part of the above theorem means the following: To obtain a deformation datum of V, map the corresponding path in the fission surface of Θ (cf.",
    "Remark 4.10) to the fission surface of Θ via the Legendre transform and read off the corresponding map given by parallel transport in V (up to a sign).",
    "Note that the path from m I to m J in the picture before Fourier transform that we obtain is not a path associated to a Stokes arrow of V. We will make this explicit in many examples in Section 6.",
    "With the relations developed in the previous subsections, this is the statement of the results in [Moc25, §10.5] (see also [Moc25, §8.9] for more explicit descriptions of the Stokes shells) in our case.",
